{"key":"post-7169216","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>7169216</id>\n<content>That looks like a good one.  All quality hygrometers need to be calibrated on purchase, and weekly for a month or two thereafter.  They have a hair, often a human hair with tension on it connected to a spring.  As the hair absorbs moisture and/or dries out, it expands and contracts, working the gage.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Wrap it up in a damp bath towel for an hour, and then unwrap the towel and adjust so the dial reads 98%.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>7169298</next>\n<prev>7169034</prev>\n<first>7169034</first>\n<last>7169298</last>\n<when>1184307522</when>\n<utime>07/13/07 09:18 AM</utime>\n</post>"}